{"title_page": "Metalogix Software", "text_new": "{{Undisclosed paid|date=March 2020}}\n{{Copypaste|url=https://www.quest.com/metalogix/|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Metalogix Software\n| logo = File:Metalogix logo.png\n| type = [[Privately held company]]\n| foundation = 2001\n| location = Aliso Viejo, CA, USA\n| industry = [[Computer software]]\n| products = Content Matrix, StoragePoint, Replicator, ControlPoint, Backup for SharePoint, Diagnostic Manager, Archive Manager for Exchange, Archive Manager for Files, Metalogix Expert, Sensitive Content Manager, Essentials for Office 365\n| parent = [[Quest Software]]\n| homepage = https://www.quest.com/metalogix/\n}}\n'''Metalogix Software''' is an [[independent software vendor]], founded in 2001 in Vancouver, British Columbia, was acquired by [[Quest Software|Quest Software, Inc.]] in July 2018. Metalogix develops, sells and provides support for content infrastructure software for [[Microsoft SharePoint]], [[Microsoft Exchange Server|Microsoft Exchange]] and [[Office 365|Microsoft Office 365]] platforms. In 2001, Metalogix became the first company to develop a [[content migration]] solution for Microsoft.<ref>Microsoft Case Study on Metalogix at http://www.microsoft.com/casestudies/Case_Study_Detail.aspx?CaseStudyID=4000010759</ref> Metalogix products allow organizations to move deprecated and custom line-of-business applications into the platform of their choice; manage storage, archiving and system performance; and protect and govern complete collaboration ecosystems.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.quest.com/metalogix/|title=Office 365 and SharePoint Content Migration and Management|website=www.quest.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nWith more and more companies making the move to Office 365, SharePoint has become the leading collaboration platform for organizations of all sizes. The acquisition of Metalogix strengthens the Quest [https://www.quest.com/solutions/microsoft-platform-management/ Microsoft Platform Management] solution portfolio by extending capabilities to support SharePoint, SharePoint Online, and OneDrive for Business.\n\n==Product portfolio==\nMetalogix\u2019s primary product is Content Matrix, which is a combination of the company's former Migration Manager and Content Manager products. It is designed to migrate significant amounts of content from legacy SharePoint environments into new SharePoint versions in one hop. Content Matrix enables the scalability that organizations need to optimally configure the migration to suit their needs and project timelines.<ref>Article on Metalogix Content Matrix 6.0 at http://www.cmswire.com/cms/information-management/migrate-from-any-version-to-sharepoint-2013-with-new-metalogix-content-matrix-60-018095.php</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Metalogix Archive Manager has editions for Exchange and Files.<ref>Article on Archive Manager 5.0 at http://www.cmswire.com/cms/information-management/metalogix-archive-manager-50-tracks-sharepoint-exchange-users-files-012188.php</ref> In 2008, Metalogix merged its [[email archiving]] business with H&S Software under the Metalogix name.<ref>Announcement on Metalogix acquiring H&S Software at http://www.metalogix.com/Promotions/Exchange-PAM.aspx</ref> In 2010, Metalogix acquired Sunbelt Exchange Archiver and File Archiver.<ref>FAQ on Metalogix acquiring Sunbelt Software at http://www.metalogix.com/Promotions/Sunbelt-FAQ.aspx</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Metalogix acquired the StoragePoint from BlueThread Technologies.<ref>Blog post on Metalogix acquiring BlueThread StoragePoint at {{cite web |url=http://socialmedia.mikegannotti.com/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=375 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-01-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322215907/http://socialmedia.mikegannotti.com/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=375 |archivedate=2010-03-22 }}</ref> StoragePoint is a SharePoint storage optimization solution that offloads unstructured SharePoint content [[data]], known as [[Binary Large Object]]s (BLOBs) from SharePoint\u2019s underlying [[SQL database]] to alternate tiers of storage.<ref>Article on Metalogix acquiring StoragePoint at http://www.cmswire.com/cms/enterprise-cms/metalogix-acquires-storagepoint-adds-external-blob-storage-to-suite-007022.php</ref> The company announced an integrated file share consolidation solution with StoragePoint and Content Matrix<ref>Article on Metalogix file share consolidation solution at http://www.cmswire.com/cms/information-management/metalogix-speeds-sharepoint-content-migration-with-integration-of-storagepoint-016749.php</ref> in July 2012. StoragePoint 4.0 was released in November 2012 with new SharePoint backup and restore features.<ref>Article on StoragePoint 4.0 at http://www.wwpi.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=15295:metalogix-debuts-storagepoint-40-to-simplify-and-speed-up-sharepoint-backup-and-restore-processes&catid=332:breaking-news&Itemid=2701751</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, Metalogix acquired Syntergy's SharePoint business,<ref>Article on Metalogix acquisition of Syntergy's SharePoint business at http://www.sharepointpromag.com/article/sharepoint/metalogix-acquires-syntergy-142472</ref> including Replicator for SharePoint, which is a web-based solution used to synchronize and manage business intelligence in real time across multiple SharePoint environments.\n\nIn August 2013, Metalogix acquired Axceler's SharePoint business,<ref>Article on Metalogix acquisition of Axceler at http://www.cmswire.com/cms/information-management/metalogix-buys-out-axcelers-sharepoint-business-022272.php</ref> including ControlPoint, which allows organizations to manage permissions, audit user and admin actions, automate and delegate SharePoint governance, clean up SharePoint content, monitor user adoption and protect against data breaches and suspicious user behavior.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn October 2013, Metalogix acquired Idera's SharePoint business,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Metalogix Acquires Idera\u2019s SharePoint Business Including Market-Leading SharePoint Backup and Diagnostic Manager|url = http://www.metalogix.com/News-Detail/13-10-23/Metalogix_Acquires_Idera_s_SharePoint_Business_Including_Market-Leading_SharePoint_Backup_and_Diagnostic_Manager.aspx?indexCatalogue=searchindex&searchQuery=idera&wordsMode=1|website = www.metalogix.com|accessdate = 2015-12-07}}</ref> including Backup for SharePoint, which ensures a comprehensive backup and restore solution for an entire SharePoint environment. Organizations can create backup sets that are highly compact and secure, enable granular restores of individual or departmental content and streamline recoveries with self-service features.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSensitive Content Manager allows users to scan, detect and classify sensitive data and PII. It also leverages the full range of SharePoint permissions management, auditing and user activity to increase the effectiveness of data loss prevention both on premises and in the cloud.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nEssentials for Office 365 provides single-console management that organizations can use to move and reorganize content from multiple cloud service providers and on-premises SharePoint and File Shares. It facilitates permissions and license management and helps gather key intelligence about user adoption.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDiagnostic Manager allows organizations to view the health and performance of their SharePoint environment from a single dashboard. It offers the creation of custom reports based on issues unique to a specific environment.\n\nMetalogix Expert is freeware offered by Quest Software to assess source SharePoint environments to help guide migration projects with the insight needed to plan a successful SharePoint migration, optimize your storage infrastructure and safeguard against security risk.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Company==\nMetalogix is part of [[Quest Software|Quest Software, Inc.]] having been acquired in July 2018. Following the acquisition, Microsoft named Metalogix a Charter Member of the Microsoft Content Services Partner Program, along with the designation \u201cMicrosoft Preferred.\u201d The company was named to the Inc. magazine's 2012 \"Inc. 500\" list of the fastest-growing companies in America.<ref>Inc 500 profile on Metalogix at http://www.inc.com/inc5000/profile/metalogix</ref>\n\nMetalogix currently has helped more than 20,000 enterprise customers globally,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Company Overview {{!}} Metalogix|url = http://www.metalogix.com/About/Company-Overview.aspx|website = www.metalogix.com|accessdate = 2015-12-07}}</ref> including organizations in the legal, financial, technology,<ref>Article on Kahuna Ventures at http://hosted-exchange.tmcnet.com/topics/unified-communications/articles/238051-kahuna-ventures-selects-metalogix-archive-manager.htm</ref> manufacturing, health care, apparel,<ref>Article on Sportif USA at http://www.kmworld.com/Articles/News/KM-In-Practice/Sportif-gets-grip-on-escalating-e-mail-dilemma-78812.aspx</ref> [[public sector]], real estate <ref>ClearPeople press release on Knight Frank at {{cite web |url=http://www.clearpeople.com/sitecore/content/ClearPeople/Global/Items/News/2011/Knight%20Frank%20release.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120729225635/http://www.clearpeople.com/sitecore/content/ClearPeople/Global/Items/News/2011/Knight%20Frank%20release.aspx |archivedate=2012-07-29 }}</ref> and academic industry verticals.\n\nIn 2018, Metalogix was acquired by [[Quest Software]], a software company headquartered in [[Aliso Viejo, California]] with global offices in [[Dublin, Ohio]]; [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax, Canada]]; Kanata, Canada; [[Saint Petersburg|Saint-Petersburg, Russia]]; [[Cork (city)|Cork, Ireland]]; [[Zhuhai|Zhuhai, China]]; [[Veracruz, Panama]] and [[S\u00e3o Paulo|Sao Paulo, Brazil]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cmswire.com/news/topic/metalogix CMS Wire articles on Metalogix]\n\n{{Quest Software Inc}}\n\n[[Category:Software companies based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Software companies established in 2001]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2018 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Quest Software]]\n[[Category:Software companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Undisclosed paid|date=March 2020}}\n{{Copypaste|url=https://www.quest.com/metalogix/|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Metalogix Software\n| logo = File:Metalogix logo.png\n| type = [[Privately held company]]\n| foundation = 2001\n| location = Aliso Viejo, CA, USA\n| industry = [[Computer software]]\n| products = Content Matrix, StoragePoint, Replicator, ControlPoint, Backup for SharePoint, Diagnostic Manager, Archive Manager for Exchange, Archive Manager for Files, Metalogix Expert, Sensitive Content Manager, Essentials for Office 365\n| parent = [[Quest Software]]\n| homepage = https://www.quest.com/metalogix/\n}}\n'''Metalogix Software''' is an [[independent software vendor]], founded in 2001 in Vancouver, British Columbia, was acquired by [[Quest Software|Quest Software, Inc.]] in July 2018. Metalogix develops, sells and provides support for content infrastructure software for [[Microsoft SharePoint]], [[Microsoft Exchange Server|Microsoft Exchange]] and [[Office 365|Microsoft Office 365]] platforms. In 2001, Metalogix became the first company to develop a [[content migration]] solution for Microsoft.<ref>Microsoft Case Study on Metalogix at http://www.microsoft.com/casestudies/Case_Study_Detail.aspx?CaseStudyID=4000010759</ref> Metalogix products allow organizations to move deprecated and custom line-of-business applications into the platform of their choice; manage storage, archiving and system performance; and protect and govern complete collaboration ecosystems.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.quest.com/metalogix/|title=Office 365 and SharePoint Content Migration and Management|website=www.quest.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nWith more and more companies making the move to Office 365, SharePoint has become the leading collaboration platform for organizations of all sizes. The acquisition of Metalogix strengthens the Quest [https://www.quest.com/solutions/microsoft-platform-management/ Microsoft Platform Management] solution portfolio by extending capabilities to support SharePoint, SharePoint Online, and OneDrive for Business.\n\n==Product roadmap==\nMetalogix\u2019s primary product is Content Matrix, which is a combination of the company's former Migration Manager and Content Manager products. It is designed to migrate significant amounts of content from legacy SharePoint environments into new SharePoint versions in one hop. Content Matrix enables the scalability that organizations need to optimally configure the migration to suit their needs and project timelines.<ref>Article on Metalogix Content Matrix 6.0 at http://www.cmswire.com/cms/information-management/migrate-from-any-version-to-sharepoint-2013-with-new-metalogix-content-matrix-60-018095.php</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Metalogix Archive Manager product has editions for Exchange and Files.<ref>Article on Archive Manager 5.0 at http://www.cmswire.com/cms/information-management/metalogix-archive-manager-50-tracks-sharepoint-exchange-users-files-012188.php</ref> In 2008, Metalogix merged its [[email archiving]] business with H&S Software under the Metalogix name.<ref>Announcement on Metalogix acquiring H&S Software at http://www.metalogix.com/Promotions/Exchange-PAM.aspx</ref> In 2010, Metalogix acquired Sunbelt Exchange Archiver and File Archiver.<ref>FAQ on Metalogix acquiring Sunbelt Software at http://www.metalogix.com/Promotions/Sunbelt-FAQ.aspx</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Metalogix acquired the StoragePoint product from BlueThread Technologies.<ref>Blog post on Metalogix acquiring BlueThread StoragePoint at {{cite web |url=http://socialmedia.mikegannotti.com/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=375 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-01-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322215907/http://socialmedia.mikegannotti.com/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=375 |archivedate=2010-03-22 }}</ref> StoragePoint is a SharePoint storage optimization solution that offloads unstructured SharePoint content [[data]], known as [[Binary Large Object]]s (BLOBs) from SharePoint\u2019s underlying [[SQL database]] to alternate tiers of storage.<ref>Article on Metalogix acquiring StoragePoint at http://www.cmswire.com/cms/enterprise-cms/metalogix-acquires-storagepoint-adds-external-blob-storage-to-suite-007022.php</ref> The company announced an integrated file share consolidation solution with StoragePoint and Content Matrix<ref>Article on Metalogix file share consolidation solution at http://www.cmswire.com/cms/information-management/metalogix-speeds-sharepoint-content-migration-with-integration-of-storagepoint-016749.php</ref> in July 2012. StoragePoint 4.0 was released in November 2012 with new SharePoint backup and restore features.<ref>Article on StoragePoint 4.0 at http://www.wwpi.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=15295:metalogix-debuts-storagepoint-40-to-simplify-and-speed-up-sharepoint-backup-and-restore-processes&catid=332:breaking-news&Itemid=2701751</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, Metalogix acquired Syntergy's SharePoint business,<ref>Article on Metalogix acquisition of Syntergy's SharePoint business at http://www.sharepointpromag.com/article/sharepoint/metalogix-acquires-syntergy-142472</ref> including Replicator for SharePoint, which is a web-based solution used to synchronize and manage business intelligence in real time across multiple SharePoint environments.\n\nIn August 2013, Metalogix acquired Axceler's SharePoint business,<ref>Article on Metalogix acquisition of Axceler at http://www.cmswire.com/cms/information-management/metalogix-buys-out-axcelers-sharepoint-business-022272.php</ref> including ControlPoint, which allows organizations to manage permissions, audit user and admin actions, automate and delegate SharePoint governance, clean up SharePoint content, monitor user adoption and protect against data breaches and suspicious user behavior.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn October 2013, Metalogix acquired Idera's SharePoint business,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Metalogix Acquires Idera\u2019s SharePoint Business Including Market-Leading SharePoint Backup and Diagnostic Manager|url = http://www.metalogix.com/News-Detail/13-10-23/Metalogix_Acquires_Idera_s_SharePoint_Business_Including_Market-Leading_SharePoint_Backup_and_Diagnostic_Manager.aspx?indexCatalogue=searchindex&searchQuery=idera&wordsMode=1|website = www.metalogix.com|accessdate = 2015-12-07}}</ref> including Backup for SharePoint, which ensures a comprehensive backup and restore solution for an entire SharePoint environment. Organizations can create backup sets that are highly compact and secure, enable granular restores of individual or departmental content and streamline recoveries with self-service features.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSensitive Content Manager allows users to scan, detect and classify sensitive data and PII. It also leverages the full range of SharePoint permissions management, auditing and user activity to increase the effectiveness of data loss prevention both on premises and in the cloud.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nEssentials for Office 365 provides single-console management that organizations can use to move and reorganize content from multiple cloud service providers and on-premises SharePoint and File Shares. It facilitates permissions and license management and helps gather key intelligence about user adoption.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDiagnostic Manager allows organizations to view the health and performance of their SharePoint environment from a single dashboard. It offers the creation of custom reports based on issues unique to a specific environment.\n\nMetalogix Expert is freeware offered by Quest Software to assess source SharePoint environments to help guide migration projects with the insight needed to plan a successful SharePoint migration, optimize your storage infrastructure and safeguard against security risk.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Company==\nMetalogix is part of [[Quest Software|Quest Software, Inc.]] having been acquired in July 2018. Following the acquisition, Microsoft named Metalogix a Charter Member of the Microsoft Content Services Partner Program, along with the designation \u201cMicrosoft Preferred.\u201d The company was named to the Inc. magazine's 2012 \"Inc. 500\" list of the fastest-growing companies in America.<ref>Inc 500 profile on Metalogix at http://www.inc.com/inc5000/profile/metalogix</ref>\n\nMetalogix currently has more than 20,000 enterprise customers globally,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Company Overview {{!}} Metalogix|url = http://www.metalogix.com/About/Company-Overview.aspx|website = www.metalogix.com|accessdate = 2015-12-07}}</ref> including organizations in the legal, financial, technology,<ref>Article on Kahuna Ventures at http://hosted-exchange.tmcnet.com/topics/unified-communications/articles/238051-kahuna-ventures-selects-metalogix-archive-manager.htm</ref> manufacturing, health care, apparel,<ref>Article on Sportif USA at http://www.kmworld.com/Articles/News/KM-In-Practice/Sportif-gets-grip-on-escalating-e-mail-dilemma-78812.aspx</ref> [[public sector]], real estate <ref>ClearPeople press release on Knight Frank at {{cite web |url=http://www.clearpeople.com/sitecore/content/ClearPeople/Global/Items/News/2011/Knight%20Frank%20release.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120729225635/http://www.clearpeople.com/sitecore/content/ClearPeople/Global/Items/News/2011/Knight%20Frank%20release.aspx |archivedate=2012-07-29 }}</ref> and academic industry verticals.\n\nIn 2018, Metalogix was acquired by [[Quest Software]], a software company headquartered in [[Aliso Viejo, California]] with global offices in [[Dublin, Ohio]]; [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax, Canada]]; Kanata, Canada; [[Saint Petersburg|Saint-Petersburg, Russia]]; [[Cork (city)|Cork, Ireland]]; [[Zhuhai|Zhuhai, China]]; [[Veracruz, Panama]] and [[S\u00e3o Paulo|Sao Paulo, Brazil]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cmswire.com/news/topic/metalogix CMS Wire articles on Metalogix]\n\n{{Quest Software Inc}}\n\n[[Category:Software companies based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Software companies established in 2001]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2018 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Quest Software]]\n[[Category:Software companies of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Kburnside 13", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduct roadmap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metalogix_Software"}
{"title_page": "Peter J. N. Sinclair", "text_new": "{{short description|British economist}}\n'''Peter James Niven Sinclair''' (18 September 1946&nbsp;\u2013 31 March 2020)<ref name=OGcab>''Old Greshamian Club Address Book'' (Cheverton & Son Ltd., Cromer, 1999) p. 43</ref> was a British economist. He was a Professor, and subsequently an Emeritus Professor, in Economics at the [[University of Birmingham]]. Previously, he had been a fellow and tutor at [[Brasenose College, Oxford]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nSinclair grew up in London and [[Norfolk]] and was educated at [[Gresham's School]]<ref name=OGcab/> and the University of Oxford, where he gained his BA and doctorate. His first job, before working at the University of Oxford, was in the export department of [[The Linde Group|Linde AG]] in Germany. This sharpened his lifelong interest in international economics.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Career==\nPeter Sinclair taught at Oxford for twenty-four years, mainly in economic theory, [[monetary policy]] and [[international economics]], as fellow and tutor in Economics at [[Brasenose College]] where he was a popular junior Dean. From 1994 he was Professor of Economics at the University of Birmingham.\n\nSinclair published widely on a range of economic subjects, including the optimal rate of inflation, [[Monetary reform#Central Bank Independence|central bank independence]], the costs and benefits of [[monetary union]], and international trade policy. He became Director of the [[Bank of England]]'s [[Centre for Central Banking Studies]] in 2000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/publications/news/2000/014.htm |title=New Director for BOE Centre for Central Banking Studies |work=News Release |publisher=[[Bank of England]] |date=February 14, 2000}}</ref> in which role he taught central bank staff from all over the world, both in London and overseas.  Sinclair maintained a connection with the Bank of England after leaving CCBS in 2008, including as a visiting academic, advising on research and teaching graduate entrants for many years. He also advised numerous overseas central banks. He contributed to a number of CCBS and Bank of England publications, including the Bank's  Quarterly Bulletin, often providing an academic's perspective on contemporary monetary issues.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://search.bankofengland.co.uk/search?q=%22Peter+Sinclair%22+%22Quarterly+Bulletin%22&submit.x=8&submit.y=13&entqr=0&ud=1&sort=date:D:L:d1&output=xml_no_dtd&oe=UTF-8&ie=UTF-8&client=default_frontend&proxystylesheet=default_frontend&site=default_collection |title=Search Results for \"Peter Sinclair\" \"Quarterly Bulletin\" |publisher=[[Bank of England]] |accessdate=2010-04-29 }}</ref>\n\nHe was the author of numerous articles and books on economics, one written with his first wife (now deceased) the economist Shelagh Heffernan, who was Professor of Banking and Finance at the [[Cass Business School]], [[City University London]]. His main research interests included inflation, unemployment, and tax questions, often in the open economy setting. He served as a consultant to the [[Financial Services Authority]], the [[Treasury]] and the [[U.S. Department of Labor]]. A visiting professor at the [[University of British Columbia]] and [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] in Canada, he also lectured in China, France, Germany, Greece, Ireland, Italy, Japan, Lesotho, Poland, Russia, and the United States. He was visiting professor at the [[London School of Economics]] and [[University of Warwick]], and chairman of the [[Royal Economic Society Easter School]], and the International Economics Study Group. In 2016 he married the environmental artist, Jayne Ivimey. His non-economics interests included architecture, history, and languages.\n\n==Former students==\nSinclair's most notable former student was [[David Cameron]].<ref>{{Cite book|first=Francis|last=Elliott|title=Cameron: The Rise of the New Conservative|page=67|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SgK940c6AF0C|isbn=9780007243662|publisher=HarperCollins UK|year=2007 }}</ref>  Others include [[King Letsie III]], [[Camilla Cavendish]], [[Peter Conradi]], [[Diane Coyle]], [[Tim Harford]], Lieutenant General [[Michelle D. Johnson]], [[Dave Ramsden]] and [[Guy Spier]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sinclair |first1=Peter |title=Bonuses, Credit Rating Agencies and the Credit Crunch |url=https://ideas.repec.org/p/bir/birmec/08-05.html}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nHe died of [[Covid-19]] on 31 March 2020 after battling the disease for a number of weeks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: David Cameron's tutor Prof Peter Sinclair dies |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-birmingham-52118901 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sinclair, Peter J.N.}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Academics of Cass Business School]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British economists]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gresham's School]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:21st-century economists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British economist}}\n'''Peter James Niven Sinclair''' (18 September 1946&nbsp;\u2013 31 March 2020)<ref name=OGcab>''Old Greshamian Club Address Book'' (Cheverton & Son Ltd., Cromer, 1999) p. 43</ref> was a British economist. He was a Professor in Economics at the [[University of Birmingham]]. Previously, he was a fellow and tutor at [[Brasenose College, Oxford]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nSinclair grew up in London and [[Norfolk]] and was educated at [[Gresham's School]]<ref name=OGcab/> and the University of Oxford, where he gained his BA and doctorate. His first job, before the university, was in the export department of [[The Linde Group|Linde AG]] in Germany. This sharpened his lifelong interest in international economics.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Career==\nPeter Sinclair taught at Oxford for twenty-four years, mainly in economic theory, [[monetary policy]] and [[international economics]], as fellow and tutor in economics at [[Brasenose College]] where he was a popular junior Dean. Since 1994 he was Professor of Economics at the University of Birmingham.\n\nSinclair published widely on a range of economic subjects, including the optimal rate of inflation, [[Monetary reform#Central Bank Independence|central bank independence]], the costs and benefits of [[monetary union]], and international trade policy. He became Director of the [[Bank of England]]'s [[Centre for Central Banking Studies]] in 2000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/publications/news/2000/014.htm |title=New Director for BOE Centre for Central Banking Studies |work=News Release |publisher=[[Bank of England]] |date=February 14, 2000}}</ref> in which role he taught central bank staff from all over the world, both in London and overseas.  Sinclair maintained a connection with the Bank of England after leaving CCBS in 2008, including as a visiting academic, advising on research and teaching graduate entrants for many years. He also advised numerous overseas central banks. He contributed to a number of CCBS and Bank of England publications, including the Bank's  Quarterly Bulletin, often providing an academic's perspective on contemporary monetary issues.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://search.bankofengland.co.uk/search?q=%22Peter+Sinclair%22+%22Quarterly+Bulletin%22&submit.x=8&submit.y=13&entqr=0&ud=1&sort=date:D:L:d1&output=xml_no_dtd&oe=UTF-8&ie=UTF-8&client=default_frontend&proxystylesheet=default_frontend&site=default_collection |title=Search Results for \"Peter Sinclair\" \"Quarterly Bulletin\" |publisher=[[Bank of England]] |accessdate=2010-04-29 }}</ref>\n\nHe was the author of numerous articles and books on economics, one written with his first wife (now deceased) the economist Shelagh Heffernan, who was Professor of Banking and Finance at the [[Cass Business School]], [[City University London]]. His main research interests included inflation, unemployment, and tax questions, often in the open economy setting. He served as a consultant to the [[Financial Services Authority]], the [[Treasury]] and the [[U.S. Department of Labor]]. A visiting professor at the [[University of British Columbia]] and [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] in Canada, he also lectured in China, France, Germany, Greece, Ireland, Italy, Japan, Lesotho, Poland, Russia, and the United States. He was visiting professor at the [[London School of Economics]] and [[University of Warwick]], and chairman of the [[Royal Economic Society Easter School]], and the International Economics Study Group. In 2016 he married the environmental artist, Jayne Ivimey. His non-economics interests included architecture, history, and languages.\n\n==Former students==\nSinclair's most notable former student was [[David Cameron]].<ref>{{Cite book|first=Francis|last=Elliott|title=Cameron: The Rise of the New Conservative|page=67|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SgK940c6AF0C|isbn=9780007243662|publisher=HarperCollins UK|year=2007 }}</ref>  Others include [[King Letsie III]], [[Camilla Cavendish]], [[Peter Conradi]], [[Diane Coyle]], [[Tim Harford]], Lieutenant General [[Michelle D. Johnson]], [[Dave Ramsden]] and [[Guy Spier]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sinclair |first1=Peter |title=Bonuses, Credit Rating Agencies and the Credit Crunch |url=https://ideas.repec.org/p/bir/birmec/08-05.html}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nHe died of [[Covid-19]] on 31 March 2020 after battling the disease for a number of weeks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: David Cameron's tutor Prof Peter Sinclair dies |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-birmingham-52118901 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sinclair, Peter J.N.}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Academics of Cass Business School]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British economists]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gresham's School]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:21st-century economists]]\n", "name_user": "P J1055", "label": "safe", "comment": "Refining language, adding information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_J._N._Sinclair"}
