{"title_page": "2003 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 2003\n| team= Western Kentucky Hilltoppers\n| image = WKU Hilltoppers wordmark.png\n| image_size= 175\n| conference= Gateway Football Conference\n| division= \n| short_conf= Gateway\n| STATSRank = \n| FCSCoachRank = 7\n| record = 9\u20134\n| conf_record = 5\u20132\n| head_coach= [[David Elson]]\n| hc_year =1st\n| off_coach= \n| oc_year = \n| def_coach= \n| dc_year = \n| off_scheme= \n| def_scheme=\n| stadium= [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium]]\n| champion = \n| bowl = [[2003 NCAA Division I-AA football season |Division I-AA Playoffs]]\n| bowl_result = Lost Quarterfinals\n}}\n{{2003 Gateway Football Conference standings}}\nThe '''2003 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team''' represented [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky University]] in the [[2003 NCAA Division I-AA football season]] and were led by first year head coach [[David Elson]]. Coming off winning the NCAA Division 1-AA Championship the previous year, this team contended for [[Missouri Valley Football Conference|Gateway Football Conference]] championship but ended up finishing tied for 3rd.  They made the school\u2019s fourth straight appearance in the NCAA Division I-AA playoffs, beating [[Jacksonville State Gamecocks football|Jacksonville State]] in the first round before losing to [[Wofford Terriers football|Wofford]] in the quarterfinals.  The Hilltoppers finished the season ranked number 7 in final 1AA postseason national poll.<ref>{{cite news|title=Final Division I-AA Poll|newspaper=The Gettysburg Times|location=Gettysburg, Pennsylvania|date=December 23, 2003|page=B2|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11125749/poll_2003_1223_i_aa_tsn_final/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=May 20, 2017}}{{Open access}}</ref>\n<br><br>\nThis team included future [[National Football League|NFL]] players [[Anthony Oakley]] and [[Brian Claybourn]].  Matt Lange and Buster Ashley were named to the AP All American team and Justin Haddix was Gateway Conference Freshman of The Year.  The All-Conference team included Ashley, Jeremy Chandler, Claybourn, Erik Dandy, Lange, Karl Maslowski, Casey Rooney, Antonio Veals, Daniel Withrow, Chad Kincaid, Oakley, and Charles Thompson.<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020.]</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 2003\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = August 28\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 5\n| opponent = [[Union Bulldogs and Lady Bulldogs |Union (KY)]]\n| site_stadium = [[L. T. Smith Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Bowling Green, Kentucky]]\n| score = 51\u20133\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 6\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 5\n| opponent = [[West Virginia University Institute of Technology|West Virginia Tech]]\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 67\u20133\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 20\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 3\n| opponent = [[Eastern Kentucky Colonels football|Eastern Kentucky]]\n| opprank = 23\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 36\u20133\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 27\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| rank = 3\n| opponent = [[2003 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]]\n| opprank = \n| site_stadium = [[Jordan\u2013Hare Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Auburn, Alabama]]\n| score = 3\u201348\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 4\n| w/l = l\n| away = y\n| rank = 6\n| opponent = [[Western Illinois Leathernecks football|Western Illinois]]\n| opprank = 2\n| site_stadium = [[Hanson Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Macomb, Illinois]]\n| score = 28\u201333\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 11\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 9\n| opponent = [[Missouri State Bears and Lady Bears|Missouri State]]\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 9\u20136\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 18\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 9\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=2003|team=Illinois State Redbirds|title=Illinois State}}\n| site_stadium = [[Hancock Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Normal, Illinois]]\n| score = 27\u201324\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 25\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 8\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=2003|team=Indiana State Sycamores|title=Indiana State}}\n| site_stadium = [[Memorial Stadium (Terre Haute)|Memorial Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Terre Haute, Indiana]]\n| score = 59\u201314\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 1\n| w/l = l\n| homecoming = y\n| rank = 8\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=2003|team=Southern Illinois Salukis|title=Southern Illinois}}\n| opprank = 3\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 24\u201328\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 8\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 12\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=2003|team=Northern Iowa Panthers|title=Northern Iowa}}\n| opprank = 6\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 24\u20133\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 15\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 10\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=2002|team=Youngstown State Penguins|title=Youngstown State}}\n| site_stadium = [[Stambaugh Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Youngstown, Ohio]]\n| score = 37\u201313\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 29\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 9\n| opponent = [[Jacksonville State Gamecocks football|Jacksonville State]]\n| opprank = 17\n| gamename = I-AA Playoffs First Round\n| site_stadium = L. T. Smith Stadium\n| site_cityst = Bowling Green, KY\n| score = 45\u20137\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = December 6\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 9\n| opponent = [[Wofford Terriers football|Wofford]]\n| oppra